    {
        "content": "<p>Recall that in mathlib, a real number is an equivalence class of Cauchy sequences of rational numbers. That is, a real number consists of the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A function <code>f : ℕ → ℚ</code> (which we think of as the sequence <code>f 0</code>, <code>f 1</code>, <code>f 2</code>, ... of rational numbers)</li>\n<li>A proof that <code>f</code> is a Cauchy sequence (<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsCauSeq#doc\">docs#IsCauSeq</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We consider two such functions to be equal if they are related by the equivalence relation <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CauSeq.equiv#doc\">docs#CauSeq.equiv</a>.</p>\n<p>Now let us think about what it means for a real number to be computable. Remember that the compiler always ignores proofs. The compiler also isn't concerned with whether two real numbers are equal or not. So, from the perspective of the compiler, a real number is just a function <code>f : ℕ → ℚ</code>. This explains how <code>2 : ℝ</code> is computable: it is defined by the Cauchy sequence <code>2, 2, 2, ...</code>, or in other words, the constant function <code>(fun n ↦ 2 : ℕ → ℚ)</code>, which is computable.</p>\n<p>Lean will even evaluate <code>(2 : ℝ)</code> if you ask it to:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Data</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Real</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Basic</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Real.ofCauchy (sorry /- 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, ... -/)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The <code>sorry</code> in this output represents the proof that the sequence <code>2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, ...</code> is Cauchy, which was discarded by the compiler.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, <code>Real.pi</code> is noncomputable. It is defined in mathlib as follows: take an arbitrary root of the cosine function in the interval <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[1, 2]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, and then multiply it by two (<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Real.pi#doc\">docs#Real.pi</a>). This arbitrary choice is what makes it noncomputable. The fact that the cosine function happens to have a unique root in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[1, 2]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> doesn't help. The problem is that this definition doesn't actually construct the corresponding Cauchy sequence as a computable function.</p>\n<p>Now, it would be possible to define <code>Real.pi</code> in a computable way, as the limit of the Cauchy sequence </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>…</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\frac{4}{1}, \\frac{4}{1} - \\frac{4}{3}, \\frac{4}{1} - \\frac{4}{3} + \\frac{4}{5}, \\frac{4}{1 } - \\frac{4}{3} + \\frac{4}{5} - \\frac{4}{7}, \\ldots</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:2.0074em;vertical-align:-0.686em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.3214em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"