    {
        "content": "<p>All of these questions about computability of real numbers depend heavily on the particular construction of the real numbers in mathlib. For example, if real numbers were defined using Dedekind cuts instead of Cauchy sequences, then almost all the definitions involving real numbers in mathlib would be computable. This is because:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>a Dedekind cut is a set of rational numbers together with a proof that it really is a Dedekind cut,</li>\n<li>a set of rational numbers is really a function <code>ℚ → Prop</code>,</li>\n<li>propositions are ignored by the runtime.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>However, this would not actually be useful or good in any way. A real number would not have any data associated with it, so the fact that it could be \"computed\" is not all that impressive.</p>",
        "id": 497300223,
        "sender_full_name": "Mitchell Lee",
        "timestamp": 1738537447
    },
